Part 2: Clean data (I will clean it by renaming 4046, 4225, 4770, to small, large, xlarge. I will aslo create a new variable that groups the states and cities into the 4 main regions (west,south,east,north)). And lastly drop na vlues.

Code 
df = df.rename(columns={
    "4046": "small",
    "4225": "large",
    "4770": "xlarge"
})
df_clean = df.dropna()

    "TotalUS": "Total US", "Total U.S.": "Total US",
    "West": "West", "California": "West", "LosAngeles": "West", "SanFrancisco": "West",
    "SouthCentral": "South", "Southeast": "South", "Houston": "South", "DallasFtWorth": "South",
    "Northeast": "Northeast", "NewYork": "Northeast", "Boston": "Northeast",
    "GreatLakes": "Midwest", "Chicago": "Midwest"
}

df_clean["major_region"] = df["geography"].map(region_map)
num_geo = df_clean["geography"].nunique()

Part 5

Code 
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_boxplot, labs, theme_minimal, theme, element_text
non_metro = [
    "TotalUS", "Total U.S.", "West", "SouthCentral", "Southeast",
    "Northeast", "GreatLakes", "Midsouth", "Plains", "WestTexNewMexico", 'California', 'Great Lakes', "Los Angeles"
]

df_metro = df[~df["geography"].isin(non_metro)]

metro_avg = (
    df_metro.groupby("geography")["total_volume"]
    .mean()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
    .head(5)
)

top5 = metro_avg.index.tolist()

df_top5 = df_metro[df_metro["geography"].isin(top5)]

metrop = (
    ggplot(df_top5, aes(x="geography", y="total_volume", fill="geography"))
    + geom_boxplot()
    + labs(
        title="Total Volume Distribution for Top 5 Metro Areas",
        x="Metro Area",
        y="Total Volume"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=30, ha="right"),
        legend_position="none",
        figure_size=(10, 6)
    )
)
metrop

From the box plot we created we can see the South Central is the largest metro region of the US for avocado volume sales.

Part 8

Code 
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import (
    ggplot, aes, geom_col, facet_wrap, labs, theme_minimal, theme,
    element_text, scale_y_continuous
)
order = ["Los Angeles", "Sacramento", "San Diego", "San Francisco"]
df_ca["geography"] = pd.Categorical(df_ca["geography"], categories=order, ordered=True)
avg_sizes = (
    df_ca.groupby(["geography", "type"])[["small", "large", "xlarge"]]
    .mean()
    .reset_index() 
)
long = (
    avg_sizes.melt(id_vars=["geography", "type"],
                   value_vars=["small", "large", "xlarge"],
                   var_name="size", value_name="avg_volume")
)

group_sums = (
    long.groupby(["geography", "type"])["avg_volume"]
    .sum()
    .reset_index()
    .rename(columns={"avg_volume": "group_total"})
)
long = long.merge(group_sums, on=["geography", "type"])
long["prop"] = long["avg_volume"] / long["group_total"]
long['size']= pd.Categorical(long['size'],categories= ['xlarge','large',"small"], ordered= True)
p = (
    ggplot(long, aes(x="geography", y="prop", fill="size"))
    + geom_col()                               
    + facet_wrap("~type", nrow=1)
    + scale_y_continuous(labels=lambda v: [f"{x:.0%}" for x in v])
    + labs(
        title="Proportion of Average Hass Avocado Sales by Size",
        x="Region of California",
        y="Proportion",
        fill="size"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=20, ha="right"),
        figure_size=(10, 6)
    )
)
p

Code 
import pandas as pd
cities = ["Los Angeles", "San Diego", "Sacramento", "San Francisco"]
housing = pd.read_csv("Data/FHFA House Price Index Master.csv").dropna()
housing["place_name"] = (
    housing["place_name"]
    .astype(str)
    .replace({
        r"^San Francisco.*": "San Francisco",
        r"^Los Angeles.*": "Los Angeles",
        r"^Sacramento.*": "Sacramento",
        r"^San Diego.*": "San Diego"
    }, regex=True)
)
#| eco : true
Code 
housing = housing[housing["place_name"].isin(cities)].copy()
housing = housing.rename(columns={"place_name": "City"}) 
df_ca = df_ca.rename(columns={"geography": "City"})
Code 
merged = pd.merge(df_ca, housing, on="City", how="inner")
merged["average_price_scaled"] = merged["average_price"] * 100
summary = (
    merged.groupby("City", as_index=False)[["average_price_scaled", "total_volume", "index_nsa"]]
    .mean()
)
Code 
long_price_index = summary.melt(
    id_vars="City",
    value_vars=["average_price_scaled", "index_nsa"],
    var_name="Metric",
    value_name="Value"
)
Code 
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_bar, labs, theme_minimal, theme, element_text, position_dodge, geom_point, geom_smooth
p_bars = (
    ggplot(long_price_index, aes(x="City", y="Value", fill="Metric"))
    + geom_bar(stat="identity", position=position_dodge(width=0.8))
    + labs(
        title="Avocado Prices vs Housing Index (Four CA Cities)",
        x="City",
        y="Value",
        fill="Metric"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=15, ha="right"), figure_size=(10, 6))
)
p_bars

As we can see we from the chart we can not see a direct influence of avocado prices on house prices. While San Fran is the most expeensive for both, sacromento has the 2nd most expesnive avocado prices but has the cheapest home prices.
